{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17502346","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17502346"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:42:37+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:42:37+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1848"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1848","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1848"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.22,0.3,0.13,0.3,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1848"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107087"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1848","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1848"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1848"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89551"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"36"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1984"},{"type":"tags","id":"2924"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"31545"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31546"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35547"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107087","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/107087"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 42-year-old woman is being assessed for unremitting pain from a 7 mm stone impacted in the distal left ureter. Apart from the pain she is otherwise stable with a blood pressure of 110/70 mmHg, pulse 85/min, respiratory rate: 14/min and temperature 37.2\u2103. A urine microscopy, culture and sensitivity (MCS) is proceeding. Because of the severe pain that is unresponsive to maximum analgesia, active intervention is being considered.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management strategy?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Ureteric stent placement","Ureteroscopic laser lithotripsy","Ureteroscopic basket extraction","Extracorporeal shockwave lithotripsy","Percutaneous nephrolithotomy"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EUreteric stones 4 mm or less, will usually pass spontaneously and those 5-7 mm may still pass of their own accord, but the success rate falls to less than 60%. Larger stones will usually require some form of intervention.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis calculus will require intervention and it is too large to be safely extracted with a stone basket. For \u003Cstrong\u003Ebasket extraction\u003C/strong\u003E, \u0026lt;5mm is likely to be more suitable for this approach depending on the morphology of the calculus and the anatomy of the patient\u0027s ureter. Trying to remove larger stones with basket extraction alone is likely to lead to significant ureteric trauma and potential development of secondary ureteric strictures.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFor a stone this size, \u003Cstrong\u003Elaser lithotripsy\u003C/strong\u003E is the preferred approach. In this endoscopic procedure an instrument is advanced to the stone in the ureter and a fibre optic laser fibre is inserted through the endoscope. The laser fibre is then used to direct focussed pulses of energy onto the calculus causing it to fragment into smaller, passable pieces.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIf there was evidence of urinary sepsis, then immediate decompression with a \u003Cstrong\u003Eureteric stent\u003C/strong\u003E would be appropriate and ureteroscopy and lithotripsy extremely hazardous with the risk of overwhelming urosepsis. However, in this setting where there is no clinical suspicion of concurrent urinary tract infection, primary ureteroscopy is reasonable to attempt with passage of a stent if the ureteric anatomy proved unfavourable (e.g. too tight to advanced the scope)\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EExtracorporeal shockwave lithotripsy\u003C/strong\u003E is unsuitable in this setting because it requires multiple treatment sessions. The patient\u0027s extreme pain makes prompt correction of the underlying problem in the most expeditious fashion preferable. Also few centres have current experience with ESWL whereas laser lithotripsy capability is almost ubiquitous across Urology units in Australia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPercutaneous nephrolithotomy\u003C/strong\u003E is not indicated for distal ureteric stones and is reserved for larger stones in the kidney.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Some form of intervention should always be considered for any ureteric stone over 5 mm."],"references":["Arumuham V, Byroft J. The Management of Urolithiasis. Surgery. 2016;34(7):352-360","Turk C, Petrik A, Sarica K, Seitz C, Skolarikos A, Straub M, et al. EAU Guidelines on Interventional Treatment for Urolithiasis. Eur Urol. 2016;69(3):475-82."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89551"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1848"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89551","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/89551"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-25T06:52:55+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-25T06:52:55+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1848"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107087"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"36","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/36"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd43","name":"Urology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}